article.description:
Don Chaney didn't need to think long when asked
if his New York Knicks put forth their best defensive effort of the
season against the Rockets.
article.headline: Franchise-low shooting nets another defeat for Rockets
article.linkText: Knicks' defense limits Rockets to just 29 percent shooting
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Don Chaney didn't need to think long when asked if his New York Knicks put forth their best defensive effort of the season against the Houston Rockets. ''It could be,'' Chaney said after a 99-83 victory Friday night. ''Yes, considering how explosive they are offensively, I'd have to say it is. You have to give credit to our defense.'' The Rockets shot a franchise-low 29.5 percent from the field, including 10-for-37 the second half, to drop their season-high third consecutive game. New York's defense rose stiffened in the early minutes of the fourth quarter, when the Knicks outscored Houston 16-2 over a span of four minutes, 25 seconds. Allan Houston, who had 20 points, thought that run was easy to analyze. ''Defense was the key then,'' Houston said. ''We were attacking them aggressively. We got a lot of steals and rebounds and deflections. When you do that, it ignites a lot on the other end.'' Latrell Sprewell had 21 points for the Knicks. Charlie Ward scored all nine of his points during the big fourth-quarter run that opened up an 82-62 lead, New York's largest of the night. Michael Doleac scored a season-high 15, while Clarence Weatherspoon had 10 rebounds to go with eight points as the bench contributed 41 points and 23 rebounds. ''Our bench was great,'' Chaney said. ''If we can continue to have our bench guys come in and play well, it will give our starters a rest.'' The Rockets had few excuses for their poor offensive performance. ''It was a nightmare,'' coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ''Getting the shots you want and not being able to put it in the hole. Twenty-nine percent. We missed layups, we missed open shots and then it became a grind. ''You've got to give them credit. Their guys with people right on them knocked down shots.'' Glen Rice, who had three points in 23 minutes of play, was just as unhappy. ''I think even if we had not had three days off before this would be frustrating,'' Rice said. ''We didn't play basketball the way the Houston Rockets can play. It was disappointing.'' Steve Francis had 27 points to lead Houston. Francis hit two 3s in a 10-0 run that gave the Rockets a 15-8 lead with 5:35 to play in the first quarter. But the Knicks outscored Houston 16-5 the rest of the period, with Sprewell scoring eight, for a 24-20 lead after one quarter. New York hit nine of its first 13 shots in the second quarter to lead 42-34 with 3:54 to play in the half. Maurice Taylor's 12 points off the bench kept the Knicks from running away with it. The Knicks, who led 50-41 at halftime, stretched their lead to as many as 12 in the third quarter as Sprewell, Doleac and Howard Eisley each scored five points. New York then scored the first nine points of the fourth to take its big lead. Game notes
The Rockets' previous franchise low for field goal shooting percentage was 29.9 percent against Sacramento March 28, 2002 ... Rockets are first in the NBA in fewest fouls a game at 18.59 ... Yao Ming had one block to end a string of six games in which he has had at least three a game. ... The Knicks, who play at Dallas on Saturday, are 2-3 in the first of back-to-back games and 0-4 in the second games.
